1
00:00:04,651 --> 00:00:11,871
A few years back, someone wrote
an article, an essay.

2
00:00:11,871 --> 00:00:16,314
The hook, the title, was: 
‘Is Google Making us Stupid?’

3
00:00:16,576 --> 00:00:19,712
[Spiritual Visual Media]

4
00:00:19,912 --> 00:00:23,450
He’s not really suggesting 
that Google is making us stupid,

5
00:00:23,450 --> 00:00:26,238
but he wants to catch
the reader’s attention,

6
00:00:26,238 --> 00:00:27,475
so that’s the title he gave:

7
00:00:27,475 --> 00:00:29,885
‘Is Google Making us Stupid?’

8
00:00:29,901 --> 00:00:33,623
And he’s written 
an entire book about it,

9
00:00:33,623 --> 00:00:38,629
but part of it, in summary, 
is that he’s saying,

10
00:00:38,675 --> 00:00:42,575
like, going back to 
the famous Marshall McLuhan,

11
00:00:42,575 --> 00:00:46,037
“The medium is the message.”

12
00:00:46,068 --> 00:00:51,782
So much of the way 
the internet is arranged,

13
00:00:51,798 --> 00:00:56,697
and the content distributed,

14
00:00:58,729 --> 00:01:04,549
has altered the reading patterns
and habits of people,

15
00:01:05,456 --> 00:01:09,952
and even people
who were deep readers,

16
00:01:09,952 --> 00:01:15,459
meaning: people who read
a book a week, or more,

17
00:01:15,459 --> 00:01:18,509
or you know,
regularly read full books,

18
00:01:18,509 --> 00:01:22,239
they noticed that by consuming
information on the internet,

19
00:01:22,239 --> 00:01:25,314
it’s become more or less,
you know:

20
00:01:25,314 --> 00:01:32,761
heading, or title, what you call 
a ‘lede sentence’—L.E.D.E: the lede—

21
00:01:32,761 --> 00:01:36,539
and a little paragraph,
and then ‘read more’.

22
00:01:36,539 --> 00:01:41,737
So, not a whole lot of people
are clicking on ‘read more’.

23
00:01:42,521 --> 00:01:47,843
They’re just scanning headlines,
mostly,

24
00:01:47,843 --> 00:01:51,895
then, lede sentence, 
maybe, a paragraph,

25
00:01:51,895 --> 00:01:53,964
and then, maybe,
‘read more’.

26
00:01:53,964 --> 00:01:55,685
And not only that,

27
00:01:55,685 --> 00:02:02,130
we know that Facebook
acquired Instagram,

28
00:02:02,130 --> 00:02:05,975
which we use now 
for our own promotion.

29
00:02:06,082 --> 00:02:10,037
And although they were asked,
the guys who made it

30
00:02:10,037 --> 00:02:12,437
—like, 4 or 5 guys, the company,

31
00:02:12,437 --> 00:02:15,663
they never grew the company,
they kept it small,

32
00:02:15,695 --> 00:02:18,133
it’s only 2 years old or something—

33
00:02:18,133 --> 00:02:21,387
they asked for two billion dollars.

34
00:02:21,403 --> 00:02:24,108
And Mark Zuckerberg said,
“I’ll give you one million [sic]”,

35
00:02:24,108 --> 00:02:26,499
they went, “Okay!”

36
00:02:26,499 --> 00:02:30,162
“That’s okay with me, 
I’m okay with that.”

37
00:02:30,423 --> 00:02:31,805
They didn’t argue too much,

38
00:02:31,805 --> 00:02:34,972
they accepted the billion dollars.

39
00:02:35,450 --> 00:02:38,139
And people thought, 
is he foolish?

40
00:02:38,139 --> 00:02:39,984
Or does he just have
too much money to spend?

41
00:02:39,984 --> 00:02:44,086
What’s the problem?
Or, what’s the situation?

42
00:02:44,086 --> 00:02:47,318
And what he perceived,
and perhaps not he alone,

43
00:02:47,318 --> 00:02:53,120
was that Instagram had the capacity
to cannibalise Facebook,

44
00:02:53,120 --> 00:02:54,519
because as time has gone …

45
00:02:54,519 --> 00:02:58,042
Facebook was like a picture,
and then some … you know …

46
00:02:58,042 --> 00:03:00,797
and then it became mainly pictures,

47
00:03:00,797 --> 00:03:02,921
then almost only pictures,

48
00:03:02,921 --> 00:03:06,438
and Instagram just, was pictures,
from the beginning.

49
00:03:06,438 --> 00:03:10,134
So he saw: and it’s instant,
it’s immediate.

50
00:03:10,134 --> 00:03:11,603
Take the picture, 
it’s up on the net,

51
00:03:11,603 --> 00:03:17,730
you don’t have to post
in the Facebook sense.

52
00:03:17,928 --> 00:03:22,456
So, some people 
have made the case that

53
00:03:22,456 --> 00:03:27,384
everything has shifted
towards visual media.

54
00:03:27,655 --> 00:03:32,204
And this is the point I would like 
to make in a round-about way,

55
00:03:32,204 --> 00:03:43,478
One of the famous axioms or maxims
of writing is: show, don’t tell.

56
00:03:43,654 --> 00:03:47,072
The good writers,
they write things in such a way

57
00:03:47,072 --> 00:03:50,547
that you get the picture,
so to speak.

58
00:03:50,547 --> 00:03:53,203
They don’t tell you exactly 
what it is,

59
00:03:53,203 --> 00:03:56,256
they show what it is by, 
you know,

60
00:03:56,256 --> 00:03:59,257
to get heady and intellectual, 
what T.S.Elliot called

61
00:03:59,257 --> 00:04:02,254
‘the objective co-relative’, 
which means,

62
00:04:02,254 --> 00:04:07,946
whatever the author has in mind, 
there’s an objective co-relative,

63
00:04:07,946 --> 00:04:10,770
meaning: words, images, etc.

64
00:04:10,770 --> 00:04:12,978
that if they’re assembled 
in a proper way

65
00:04:12,978 --> 00:04:17,173
will convey that idea
or concept to the person.

66
00:04:17,173 --> 00:04:20,019
That’s the idea
in summary form.

67
00:04:20,019 --> 00:04:23,042
So, what I’m going full-circle to is

68
00:04:23,042 --> 00:04:25,757
those who fear that visual media

69
00:04:25,757 --> 00:04:30,520
will eclipse literary 
and all other forms of media,

70
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:33,522
well … 
the literary media to begin with

71
00:04:33,522 --> 00:04:38,227
was to give you an image, 
a concept, some vision.

72
00:04:38,227 --> 00:04:41,328
It’s been said, ‘the artist project‘,

73
00:04:41,328 --> 00:04:43,443
and by that I don’t just mean 
people who paint,

74
00:04:43,443 --> 00:04:48,127
but art as a whole:
artists, writers, etc.

75
00:04:48,127 --> 00:04:51,445
It’s been said,
“To give people new eyes,

76
00:04:51,445 --> 00:04:56,013
new vision, new perspective, 
a new way of seeing.”

77
00:04:56,013 --> 00:05:00,499
That’s why in art, they study 
all the intricacies of that,

78
00:05:00,499 --> 00:05:03,090
like contrapposto,
the first time somebody

79
00:05:03,090 --> 00:05:07,372
had somebody move 
their body a little,

80
00:05:07,372 --> 00:05:10,728
we see those
old Egyptian things,

81
00:05:10,728 --> 00:05:12,379
and the Greek thing,

82
00:05:12,379 --> 00:05:15,255
and then somebody actually
had somebody

83
00:05:15,255 --> 00:05:19,461
move a little, contrapposto, 
contra-position.

84
00:05:19,461 --> 00:05:22,281
And other things.

85
00:05:22,281 --> 00:05:24,901
So, they made a big deal out of it,

86
00:05:24,901 --> 00:05:27,506
in terms of, 
it was artists giving people

87
00:05:27,506 --> 00:05:30,980
a new way of seeing things, 
a new perspective.

88
00:05:30,980 --> 00:05:33,327
Well, interestingly to us,
that’s really

89
00:05:33,327 --> 00:05:35,720
what the spiritual project is.

90
00:05:35,720 --> 00:05:37,859
As Guru Mahārāj said,
“What is your service?

91
00:05:37,859 --> 00:05:40,921
To acquire the proper angle of vision.”

92
00:05:40,921 --> 00:05:42,744
Sambandha-jñān, etc.

93
00:05:42,744 --> 00:05:45,388
It’s acquiring
the proper angle of vision.

94
00:05:45,388 --> 00:05:50,136
Om ajñāna-timirāndhasya
is acquiring the proper angle of vision.

95
00:05:50,136 --> 00:05:55,509
So really
the spiritual project is similar,

96
00:05:55,509 --> 00:05:59,405
but deeper.
Dive deep into reality.

97
00:05:59,405 --> 00:06:04,304
If we take it that art, at it’s best,
is some sort of representation

98
00:06:04,304 --> 00:06:10,832
of truth, or reality, then concede that

99
00:06:10,832 --> 00:06:13,589
and say 
“Yes, then we should dive deep

100
00:06:13,589 --> 00:06:16,607
into that reality, 
beyond the superficial aspects.”

